<TITLE> $130m IDA credit to improve secondary education </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 15 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh has signed a $130.7 million credit agreement with the International Development Association to improve the quality of secondary education. The money will fund The Secondary Education Quality and Access Enhancement Project aimed at improving secondary educational performance with emphasis on English language and Mathematics. The project, covering 121 upazilas, will provide stipends to poor girls and boys. Mohammad Mejbahuddin, additional secretary of Economic Relations Division, and Vinaya Swaroop, acting country director of the World Bank signed the agreement at finance ministry. The credit deal from the World Bank's concessionary arm has 40 years to maturity, including a 10-year grace period, and carries a service charge of 0.75 percent. b
